First, we show that the subobject poset of P is a lattice.
  Let S and T be subfunctors of P. Then:

the meet is given by (P\wedge  Q)X = PX\cap  QX;

the join is given by (P\vee  Q)X = PX\cup  QX;

the implication is given by (P\Rightarrow  Q)X = \{x\in  PX: \text { for all }     Y\xrightarrow {f} X\in  C, \text { if } Pf(x)\in  SY \text { then } Pf(x)\in  TY\}.

To see the translation: given a subfunctor G\hookrightarrow  C(-, x), we identify
  each element m\in  Gz with its image under the inclusion into C(z, x).
  Naturality of these inclusions asserts that, given z'\xrightarrow {f} z, 




